The very soldiers he had brought with him from Spain, already disgusted by the long march they had been forced to make, resented his untimely attempts to maintain the ancient discipline, had had their hearts stolen away from him on the march by the courtly manners and friendly open ways of Salvius Otho, and secretly murmured that they to whom he owed everything bad received no adequate recognition or reward. The exasperation of the praetorians, however, was much greater and more deeply rooted.
